The final animal Ms Lutz looks at is the grasshopper, which transports air around its using tracheal tubes.

Here the grasshopper is used as a representation of all insects. 

They do not have lungs, and instead pump their abdomens to change the volume of their air sacs.

However saying insets ‘breathe’ is a bit of a misnomer as without lungs oxygen is not transported around their circulatory system.

Instead, they use the tracheal system of tubes to move gas around their body.

When air reaches a small tube called the tracheole, the oxygen dissolves into the tracheole liquid.

Through diffusion it then enters cells, with carbon dioxide moving the other way.

Using muscle contractions, insects can then control their respiration to a limited degree. 

