Last month Ms Lutz created animations to show different flight techniques in animals.

Each is composed of 15 frames based on traced body positions of the animals from slow-motion videos.

Specific points on the wings were then marked at each of the 15 frames and connected using imaginary curves.

This creates the sweeping arcs of colour seen, which track the motion and direction of the wings as they move.

They reveal how different animals fly with a different profile, and also how wings cope with animals of different sizes.

Ms Lutz explains that she used a programme called Matlab to create the animations, based on previous work she performed with larvae.

